? DNS - domain name system                USER sends request -> DNS resolver -> Root server -> TLD -> (Authoritative) Name Server ( looks at the zone files & record) -> DNS resolver -> USER  

DNS allows us to keep track of websites instead of IP addresses
- Translate domain names into IP Addresses  -
- Simplifies navigation across the internet - 
- You write the domain name but the computers are talking via IP Addresses - 

DNS components :

Name servers - they load DNS settings and configurations 
(authoritative/recursive)
- Hold the actual DNS records and when queried hold info like ip addresses (authoritative)
- Don’t hold actual DNS record and instead query them thru other name servers on behalf of their client (recursive)

User query - (google.com) -> DNS server (authoritative) 
-> returns the name spaces  (google.com) is hosted on 

Command : dig ns google.com  /  dig +short ns google.com


*^ Zone files - stored inside name servers & store information about the domain 
- They help name servers about how to get to domain and queries on domain if the name space doesn’t know 
- They organise and readable format 



DNS components - *record*

Zone files comprised of multiple resource records  - info about hosts , name servers etc 
Comprised of : _

- Record name - The domain name being queried
- TTL ( time to live) how long record is valid b4 refresh required 
- Class - name space of the record info 
- Type - type of record - aaaa , mx  , cname
- Data - the actual info corresponding to the record type = like ip address for an A record 


? Types of record:
- A = maps the domain name to its  ipv4 address like google.com->216.58.204.79
- AAAA = (older brother) maps the domain name to a ipv6 address
- CNAME = pointing a domain to another domain name instead of an ip address ( handy for multiple domains for the same ip address ) 
- MX = specfies a  mailserver for a domain 
- TXT = stores text info for a domain ( can insert any text into dns ) ** go back over 


? Etc/hosts file 
- A local file in commuter 
- Maps domain names to ip address in its cache 
- Take precedence over DNS for some specific scenarios 
- Always checked first before the DNS resolver looks around - good for testing and troubleshooting 


DNS Hierarchy & distribution  for google.com [ theory ]
- DNS ROOT -> points us in the direction of the .com TLD 
- TLD -> points us in the direction of the specific Zone google is in ( divided ) 
- Zone -> that google is in has a specfic zone file and is managed by name space 
- Zone file -> holds the info about google.com host/subdomains and records 
- ( in this example it holds an A RECORD) = a record maps the domain name directly to a ipv4 address  


DNS hierarchy in practice 
USER sends request -> DNS resolver -> Root server -> TLD -> (Authoritative) Name Server ( looks at the zone files & record) -> DNS resolver -> USER  


? Importance of DNS resolution for DEVOPS engineers 
- Ensures service availability 
- Essential for troubleshooting DNS issues 
- Critical for configuring and managing network services 



Domain Registrar VS DNS Hosting Provider 

Domain Registrar = you buy and register domain name ( like google.com ) 

DNS hosting provider = operates DNS name servers for you
-  provider that manages your DNS record + queries so people find your ip addresses with no issues
- Convenient  
- Ex. Like Route 53 ( AWS ) / goDaddy where you can buy the domain and then they can run ur name servers for you

